[normal]Written evidence[bold] submitted by [bold]the [bold]National Trust[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Executive summary[bold]&#xa0;[bold]1. 
[normal]National Trust is a major landowner in 
[normal]England
[normal], 
[normal]Wales
[normal] and 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] with 255,000 h
[normal]ect
[normal]a
[normal]res (ha) of countryside, 
[normal]700 k
[normal]ilo
[normal]m
[normal]etres
[normal] of coastline and 400 gardens in our care for the benefit of the nation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. Approximately half 
[normal]of this land is of h
[normal]igh nature value, accessible and  
[normal] enjoyed by million
[normal]s of people. Together with tenanted farmland, it makes a significant contribution to 
[normal]local 
[normal]and regional 
[normal]economies. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3. We recognise the harm caused by
[normal] 
[normal]Invasive Non-Native Species (
[normal]IN
[normal]NS) - be they plant diseases in
[normal] gardens
[normal] and woodlands, plants in water bodies or predatory mammals on seabird 
[normal]islands. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4. We recognise the value of both 
[normal]effective quarantine measures
[normal],
[normal] and rapid reaction to control and eradicate INNS inclu
[normal]ding plant diseases
[normal]. 
[normal] O
[normal]ur 
[normal]staff can spend up to half of their time
[normal] controlling invasive species
[normal],
[normal] at a cost of up to £12000 per h
[normal]a depending on the situation
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5. 
[normal]The draft EU Directive proposal to list 50 INNS is not sufficiently sensitive to existing risk from species and those 
[normal]native species 
[normal]that are poise
[normal]d
[normal] to cause harm in areas 
[normal]of the EU where they are not native. More emphasis should be based on risk-
[normal]base
[normal]d assessments that identify species 
[normal]of most 
[normal]concern and provide the basis for risk-
[normal]based trading.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6. 
[normal]The Invasive Non-Native
[normal] 
[normal]Species Framework Strategy
[normal]for Great Britain
[normal] (GB INNS Framework), 
[normal]in 
[normal]promoting sound 
[normal]management
[normal] of INNS, could help define what success looks like, promote more effective engagement with NGOs, and forge more citizen science and state agency based partnerships.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7. The Scottish INNS legislation looks promising, as do initiatives in 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] and the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] to tackle INNS on an island –wide basis. 
